# Learn from mistakes (operational learning)

**Spec:** [openspec/specs/operational-learning/spec.md](openspec/specs/operational-learning/spec.md) · **Log:** [LEARNINGS.md](LEARNINGS.md) at repo root.

**Does not block exploration** — [CLAUDE.md](CLAUDE.md) §2: messy iteration and imagination stay welcome; this file is for **teachable moments**, not to freeze the studio in fear of error.

## When planning or reviewing work

1. If the user mentions a **past bug**, “don’t repeat that,” or a **known pitfall**, read [LEARNINGS.md](LEARNINGS.md) and apply the **Guard** from the latest relevant entry.
2. When you **fix** a material mistake (wrong behavior, spec miss, build break, privacy slip, repeated review issue), **append** a new dated section to `LEARNINGS.md` with **Mistake / Root cause / Fix / Guard**. The guard must be concrete (spec + scenario, validation, rule, or script—not “be careful”).
3. If the user reports the **same failure class** as an existing entry, do **not** delete or rewrite the old log. Add a **new** entry, call out the repeat honestly, and **tighten** prevention (e.g. add a `#### Scenario:` in the right spec, extend the PR template, or add a check).
4. Prefer linking the **Guard** to `openspec/specs/**` or an existing command so the system enforces the lesson, not only human memory.

## What not to do

- Do not treat `LEARNINGS.md` as scratch space for secrets or client-only data (see [repo-privacy](openspec/specs/repo-privacy/spec.md)).
- Do not append noise for trivial one-off typos with no repeat risk.
